<paragraph blockId="2.[151,764,152,178]" box="[151,764,152,178]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,764,152,178]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,764,152,178]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">
Biology of 
<taxonomicName box="[284,546,152,178]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Formicapis">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[284,380,152,178]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Hoplitis</emphasis>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[397,535,152,178]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Formicapis</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[607,638,152,178]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">H.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[655,754,152,178]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Tkalcua</emphasis>
)
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="107" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,222,463]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">
<taxonomicName box="[151,395,222,247]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Formicapis">
<emphasis box="[151,241,222,247]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Hoplitis</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[257,386,223,246]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Formicapis</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
species show a close affinity to flowers of 
<taxonomicName box="[875,981,223,246]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
as pollen sources (for details see species accounts). Among the 
<taxonomicName box="[404,513,259,282]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
, herbaceous taxa such as 
<taxonomicName box="[797,900,260,283]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Fragaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[797,900,260,283]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Fragaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName box="[936,1046,258,283]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Potentilla" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[936,1046,258,283]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Potentilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the most important or even the exclusive hosts. While 
<taxonomicName authority="Romankova 1985" authorityName="Romankova" authorityYear="1985" box="[410,770,294,319]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maritima">
<emphasis box="[410,547,295,318]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">H. maritima</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Romankova" box="[561,762,294,319]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" refString="Romankova, T. G. (1985) A new subspecies of Formicapis robusta (Hym. Megachilidae) from Primorye area. Vestnik Zoologii, 6, 66 - 68 [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1985">
Romankova 
<number box="[705,762,294,319]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="1985.0">1985</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and possibly also 
<taxonomicName box="[976,1080,295,318]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="excisa">
<emphasis box="[976,1080,295,318]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">H. excisa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
might be strictly specialized on 
<taxonomicName box="[151,260,331,354]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[270,387,330,355]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robusta">
<emphasis box="[270,387,330,355]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">H. robusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is polylectic with a distinct preference for 
<taxonomicName box="[863,973,330,355]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Potentilla" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[863,973,330,355]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Potentilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[988,1056,330,355]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 – 8. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1875,1897]" captionTargetBox="[174,1392,195,1829]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[173,1393,195,1831]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1 – 8. 1: Hoplitis robusta, typical habitat in open subalpine forest with large proportion of dead wood (Swiss Alps, Sedrun, Grisons). 2: Hoplitis robusta, pollen collecting female on Potentilla erecta. 3: Hoplitis coreensis, clypeus and mandibles of female. 4: Hoplitis maritima, clypeus and mandibles of female. 5: Hoplitis maritima, tergum 7 of male. 6: Hoplitis excisa, clypeus and mandibles of female. 7: Hoplitis robusta, clypeus and mandibles of female. 8: Hoplitis robusta: tergum 7 of male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259695/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">
Fig. 
<number box="[1040,1056,331,355]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<tableCitation box="[1067,1135,330,355]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,510,533]" captionTargetBox="[159,1425,689,1423]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Pollen host spectrum of Hoplitis (Formicapis) robusta and Hoplitis (Tkalcua) zandeni based on 22 female pollen loads from 20 different localities in Switzerland (n = 13), Austria (n = 2), Finland (n = 5) and the USA (n = 2), and on 29 female pollen loads from 6 different localities on Fuerteventura (Canary Islands). For H. zandeni, results of the analysis of 14 brood cell provisions originating from 12 nests from the same locality on Fuerteventura are additionally given." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/E9F010A74835C510FF2F0FDF6FD3F7AE" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" tableUuid="E9F010A74835C510FF2F0FDF6FD3F7AE">
Tab. 
<number box="[1122,1135,331,355]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
). Both 
<taxonomicName box="[1219,1355,332,355]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maritima">
<emphasis box="[1219,1355,332,355]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">H. maritima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robusta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">H. robusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nest in insect burrows in dead wood and use chewed leaves to build cell partitions and nest plug (for details see species accounts). In the latter species, small pieces of wood are sometimes incorporated into the leaf matrix of the cell partitions.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Table-UUID="E9F010A74835C510FF2F0FDF6FD3F7AE" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/E9F010A74835C510FF2F0FDF6FD3F7AE" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" targetBox="[159,1425,689,1423]" targetIsTable="true" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,510,661]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,267,510,533]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">TABLE 1.</emphasis>
Pollen host spectrum of 
<taxonomicName box="[544,869,510,533]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robusta" subGenus="Formicapis">
<emphasis box="[544,869,510,533]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Hoplitis (Formicapis) robusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[924,1214,510,533]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zandeni" subGenus="Tkalcua">
<emphasis box="[924,1214,510,533]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Hoplitis (Tkalcua) zandeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on 22 female pollen loads from 20 different localities in Switzerland (n = 13), Austria (n = 2), Finland (n = 5) and the USA (n = 2), and on 29 female pollen loads from 6 different localities on Fuerteventura (Canary Islands). For 
<taxonomicName box="[1162,1279,574,597]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zandeni">
<emphasis box="[1162,1279,574,597]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">H. zandeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, results of the analysis of 14 brood cell provisions originating from 12 nests from the same locality on Fuerteventura are additionally given.
</paragraph>
</caption>
