<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1492,2021]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">
Information on the biology of 
<taxonomicName authority="Tkalcua" authorityName="Tkalcua" box="[561,772,1492,1517]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[561,651,1492,1517]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Hoplitis</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[673,763,1492,1517]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Tkalcua</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
is available only for 
<taxonomicName box="[1032,1158,1492,1517]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zandeni">
<emphasis box="[1032,1158,1492,1517]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">H. zandeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(for details see species account). Recent observations on Fuerteventura (Canary Islands) revealed that this species is polylectic harvesting pollen on flowers of at least six plant families (
<tableCitation box="[678,748,1564,1589]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,510,533]" captionTargetBox="[159,1425,689,1423]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Pollen host spectrum of Hoplitis (Formicapis) robusta and Hoplitis (Tkalcua) zandeni based on 22 female pollen loads from 20 different localities in Switzerland (n = 13), Austria (n = 2), Finland (n = 5) and the USA (n = 2), and on 29 female pollen loads from 6 different localities on Fuerteventura (Canary Islands). For H. zandeni, results of the analysis of 14 brood cell provisions originating from 12 nests from the same locality on Fuerteventura are additionally given." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/E9F010A74835C510FF2F0FDF6FD3F7AE" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" tableUuid="E9F010A74835C510FF2F0FDF6FD3F7AE">
Tab. 
<number box="[735,748,1564,1588]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
), but probably not on 
<taxonomicName box="[1000,1127,1564,1588]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
. Interestingly, species of 
<emphasis box="[1409,1429,1565,1588]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">H</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[160,274,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Platosmia</emphasis>
), the probable sister group of 
<emphasis box="[651,671,1601,1624]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">H</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[700,790,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Tkalcua</emphasis>
), have a strong affinity to pollen of 
<taxonomicName box="[1247,1351,1599,1624]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
and/or 
<taxonomicName authority="Muller 2015" authorityName="Muller" authorityYear="2015" box="[151,452,1636,1661]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Resedaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Capparales" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">
Resedaceae (
<bibRefCitation author="Muller" box="[297,444,1636,1661]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" refString="Muller, A. (2015) Palaearctic Hoplitis bees of the subgenus Platosmia (Megachilidae, Osmiini): biology, taxonomy and key to species. Zootaxa, 3936 (1), 71 - 81. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3936.1.3" type="journal article" year="2015">
Müller 
<number box="[384,444,1636,1661]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="2015.0">2015</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, which are also the two most important pollen host taxa exploited by 
<taxonomicName box="[1247,1370,1636,1661]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zandeni">
<emphasis box="[1247,1370,1636,1661]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">H. zandeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<tableCitation captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,510,533]" captionTargetBox="[159,1425,689,1423]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Pollen host spectrum of Hoplitis (Formicapis) robusta and Hoplitis (Tkalcua) zandeni based on 22 female pollen loads from 20 different localities in Switzerland (n = 13), Austria (n = 2), Finland (n = 5) and the USA (n = 2), and on 29 female pollen loads from 6 different localities on Fuerteventura (Canary Islands). For H. zandeni, results of the analysis of 14 brood cell provisions originating from 12 nests from the same locality on Fuerteventura are additionally given." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/E9F010A74835C510FF2F0FDF6FD3F7AE" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" tableUuid="E9F010A74835C510FF2F0FDF6FD3F7AE">
Tab. 
<number box="[151,164,1672,1696]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
). Whether this merely reflects the flower supply at the study sites or indicates some underlying phylogenetic pattern remains unclear. 
<taxonomicName box="[429,552,1708,1733]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zandeni">
<emphasis box="[429,552,1708,1733]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">H. zandeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nests in empty snail shells and constructs 
<number box="[1035,1076,1708,1732]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
brood cells per shell (
<figureCitation captionStart-0="FIGURE 9 – 14" captionStart-1="FIGURE 15 – 18" captionStartId-0="10.[151,250,1510,1532]" captionStartId-1="12.[151,250,1102,1124]" captionTargetBox-0="[152,1435,193,1487]" captionTargetBox-1="[152,1433,204,1065]" captionTargetId-0="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1489]" captionTargetId-1="figure@12.[152,1435,204,1067]" captionTargetPageId-0="10" captionTargetPageId-1="12" captionText-0="FIGURE 9 – 14. Hoplitis zandeni. 9, 10: Semidesertic habitat on sandy ground with scattered shrubs of Salsola divaricata (Amaranthaceae), Launaea arborescens (Asteraceae) and Zygophyllum fontanesii (Zygophyllaceae) (Canary Islands, Fuerteventura, Costa Calma). 11: Nest in snail shell of Theba geminata, where the female had to burrow through sand masses that blocked the shell entrance. 12: Pollen loaden female at nest entrance. 13: Opened nest with one brood cell and nest plug built inside the shell. 14: Opened nest with inner side of nest plug consisting of sand grains irregularly glued together with leaf pulp." captionText-1="FIGURE 15 – 18. Hoplitis zandeni. 15: Opened nest with threshold made of a mixture of leaf pulp and sand grains. 16. Opened nest with outer side of nest plug carefully worked with sand grains and leaf pulp to form a plane wall. 17: Yellowed leaf of Helianthemum canariense with chewing marks along apical and left margin. 18: Male resting on the ground." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/259696/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/259697/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">
Figs. 
<number pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="13.5" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="11.0">11– 16</number>
</figureCitation>
). Cell partitions and nest plug consist of chewed leaves densely mixed with sand grains (
<figureCitation box="[1280,1423,1743,1768]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 9 – 14" captionStart-1="FIGURE 15 – 18" captionStartId-0="10.[151,250,1510,1532]" captionStartId-1="12.[151,250,1102,1124]" captionTargetBox-0="[152,1435,193,1487]" captionTargetBox-1="[152,1433,204,1065]" captionTargetId-0="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1489]" captionTargetId-1="figure@12.[152,1435,204,1067]" captionTargetPageId-0="10" captionTargetPageId-1="12" captionText-0="FIGURE 9 – 14. Hoplitis zandeni. 9, 10: Semidesertic habitat on sandy ground with scattered shrubs of Salsola divaricata (Amaranthaceae), Launaea arborescens (Asteraceae) and Zygophyllum fontanesii (Zygophyllaceae) (Canary Islands, Fuerteventura, Costa Calma). 11: Nest in snail shell of Theba geminata, where the female had to burrow through sand masses that blocked the shell entrance. 12: Pollen loaden female at nest entrance. 13: Opened nest with one brood cell and nest plug built inside the shell. 14: Opened nest with inner side of nest plug consisting of sand grains irregularly glued together with leaf pulp." captionText-1="FIGURE 15 – 18. Hoplitis zandeni. 15: Opened nest with threshold made of a mixture of leaf pulp and sand grains. 16. Opened nest with outer side of nest plug carefully worked with sand grains and leaf pulp to form a plane wall. 17: Yellowed leaf of Helianthemum canariense with chewing marks along apical and left margin. 18: Male resting on the ground." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/259696/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/259697/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">
Figs. 
<number box="[1350,1423,1743,1768]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="14.5" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="13.0">13–16</number>
</figureCitation>
). Interestingly, the nest plug is not built at the shell opening as in all other snail-shell nesting osmiine bee species known so far (A. Müller unpublished) but inside the shell about 
<number box="[878,888,1816,1840]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[899,913,1816,1840]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="3.0">3</number>
to 
<number box="[950,964,1816,1840]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="1.0">1</number>
whorl behind the shell aperture (
<figureCitation box="[1339,1422,1815,1840]" captionStart="FIGURE 9 – 14" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1510,1532]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,193,1487]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1489]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 9 – 14. Hoplitis zandeni. 9, 10: Semidesertic habitat on sandy ground with scattered shrubs of Salsola divaricata (Amaranthaceae), Launaea arborescens (Asteraceae) and Zygophyllum fontanesii (Zygophyllaceae) (Canary Islands, Fuerteventura, Costa Calma). 11: Nest in snail shell of Theba geminata, where the female had to burrow through sand masses that blocked the shell entrance. 12: Pollen loaden female at nest entrance. 13: Opened nest with one brood cell and nest plug built inside the shell. 14: Opened nest with inner side of nest plug consisting of sand grains irregularly glued together with leaf pulp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/259696/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">
Fig. 
<number box="[1392,1422,1816,1840]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
). In contrast to other osmiine bee genera such as 
<taxonomicName box="[683,756,1853,1876]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[683,756,1853,1876]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Osmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[771,887,1853,1876]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Protosmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[771,887,1853,1876]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Protosmia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName box="[924,1002,1853,1876]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Wainia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[924,1002,1853,1876]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Wainia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, where nesting in empty snail shells is rather widespread (
<bibRefCitation author="Kuhlmann" box="[365,614,1887,1912]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" refString="Kuhlmann, M., Gess, F. G., Koch, F. &amp; Gess, S. K. (2011) Southern African osmiine bees: taxonomic notes, two new species, a key to Wainia, and biological observations (Hymenoptera: Anthophila: Megachilidae). Zootaxa, 3108, 1 - 24." type="journal article" year="2011">
Kuhlmann 
<emphasis box="[492,542,1887,1912]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[556,614,1888,1912]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Muller" box="[625,769,1887,1912]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" refString="Muller, A. (2016) Palaearctic osmiine bees - systematics and biology of a fascinating group of solitary bees. ETH Zurich. Available from: http: // blogs. ethz. ch / osmiini (accessed 2 March 2016)" type="journal article" year="2016">
Müller 
<number box="[709,769,1887,1912]" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" value="2016.0">2016</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), snail-shell nesting in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1141,1231,1887,1912]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1141,1231,1887,1912]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Hoplitis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been reported so far beside 
<taxonomicName box="[303,426,1924,1949]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zandeni">
<emphasis box="[303,426,1924,1949]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">H. zandeni</emphasis>
